    {
      "type": "edit",
      "id": "d9ffaf0e-e768-48e1-9e49-a9bfd7e91ac3",
      "item": {
        "id": "d9ffaf0e-e768-48e1-9e49-a9bfd7e91ac3",
        "type": "markdown",
        "text": "# Beginners guide\nIn a more formal way we can say that SSI follows 10 key principles, as first outlined by Christopher Allen:\n\n- SSI provides an independent existence and absolute control for its users, who hold the access to their own data. That means no intermediaries owning or sifting through your data: it belongs to you.\n- SSI is transparent (so that you can understand any system or algorithm involved), interoperable (so it integrates well with other systems) and portable (meaning no vendor or device lock-in). \n- SSI offers persistence (the identities will last for as long as you want them to last… no need to worry about Facebook deleting your Instagram account) and protection (erring always on the side of protecting individuals’ freedoms and rights). \n- SSI prioritises consent (users must always agree to how their identity is being used — whether that’s to disclose or restrict data) and minimisation (you should only disclose the data that you need to, supporting privacy as much as you can.) \n\n"
      },
      "date": 1628603027458
    },
